# 17.1 INTRODUCTION

Though its namesake wicker basket may be a relict, the term ‘creel’ has now become synonymous with recreational catch, and creel surveys (Table 17.1) maintain an integral role in the monitoring and management of recreational fisheries.  Following a specified survey design, through a series of interview questions and often with complementary catch measurements, creel clerks gather information on recreational fishing effort, harvest, and population parameters for target species.  When biologists complete these surveys with robust methodologies over time, the survey data can illustrate trends in harvest, contribute to fish population assessments, and inform recreational fishing regulations.

 	The importance of measuring recreational fishing effort and harvest cannot be overstated.  Recreational harvest drives population dynamics of many social, economic, and ecologically important fish species, and has caused the collapse of important fisheries (see Post et al. 2002).  To avoid collapses, there is an increasing emphasis on understanding and managing social-ecological feedbacks in recreational fisheries, and measures of effort and harvest are fundamental metrics of these processes (Ward et al. 2016).  Though fishery-independent assessment methods are highly valuable tools to monitor fish populations and help ensure sustainable fisheries, in many cases, they are impractical to implement due to financial, political, and logistical constraints.  Fishery-dependent methods, such as angler surveys, provide vital information on harvest preferences that managers can use to adjust angler regulations to maintain or restore sustainable fisheries.

 	Creel surveys are a subset of angler surveys conducted as in-person, on-site interviews.  This is an intensive survey method, often requiring a coordinated effort to collect the data.  The longest running time series of creel data, such as the Lake Opeongo creel census in Ontario, date back to the 1930s, when there was a growing recognition that recreational fishing could have negative influences on fish populations.  Historically, creel surveys have been conducted as interviews at fishery access points such as boat ramps, parking lots, and piers.  Questions traditionally focused on angler activity (e.g., intensity, duration, location, gear, and target species) with the aim of getting an estimate of total fishing effort.  Biological measurements, such as length and weight, and tissue samples often accompany the interview questions to provide additional information for population assessments.

 	The value of creel surveys principally lies in the temporal proximity of the interview questions to the recreational fishing activity of interest.  Temporary recall is, for most, better than distant recollection.  The recall bias of creel survey participants, consequently, is much lower than participants of mail, phone, and internet surveys that may be asking about fishing events days, weeks, or even months prior.  In addition, creel surveys often have an element of secondary confirmation built in with collection of the biological data sampled from the catch.  As a result, data collected from creel surveys are often more reliable estimates of angler harvest than data collected by other angler survey methods.  Even so, there are important considerations when extrapolating creel survey information to harvest estimates and for population assessments.  In this chapter, we discuss creel survey questions, sampling design, analyses, and emerging applications.

# 17.2 CREEL SURVEY FRAMING

Creel surveys are often designed to address specific management or research questions.  Example questions that can be addressed with creel surveys include: What is the daytime fishing pressure on Pelican Lake (on Valentine National Wildlife Refuge) during April-October?, What is the catch rate of largemouth bass by anglers targeting largemouth bass in Fremont Lakes (a complex of gravel pits) during the past 10 years?,  How many walleye did anglers harvest from Calamus Reservoir during April 2022?,  What is fishing mortality (F) for rainbow trout in the Madison River?,  What portion of fishing trips comprised harvesting a bag limit of crappie?,  What portion of stocked rainbow trout (put-and-take fishery) is harvested?, What portion of anglers on Toledo Bend Reservoir is non-residents?, and How many anglers are fishing with live bait?  Temporal and spatial scales of interest are always defined or implied by the research question; if not, then the research question should be revised.  These scales provide boundaries on when and where sampling should occur.

	There are numerous theories in social sciences that are relevant to angler surveys, especially the responses provided by participants.  For example, rational choice theory states that people are basically rational and are able to calculate costs and benefits of actions and act accordingly (Allingham 2002).  Thus, participants should provide rational answers to questions we ask, assuming the questions we ask are appropriate and clearly stated.  However, game theory states that human interactions are a game to be won (Camerer 1997).  Thus, participants should provide “skewed” answers to questions we ask when they believe there is something to be gained (e.g., placing a low economic value on an activity that they worry may be taxed).  It is helpful for biologists to be familiar with various theories in social sciences (Table 17.2), especially when working on angler surveys and analyzing data provided by anglers.

# 17.2.1 Sampling Frame

	The basis of all creel surveys is the sampling frame, or population of inference.  The sampling frame dictates sampling design, analysis and interpretation, and is especially important for determining non-response biases present in each creel survey.  Sometimes, anglers are unwilling or unable to participate in an interview.  A non-response bias exists if the metrics being assessed differ in meaningful ways between respondents and non-respondents.  For example, let us consider an urban fishery comprised of two angler groups, a group of 14-year-old users that ride bicycles to the lake and a group of 35-year-old users that drive automobiles transporting kayaks to the lake.  Frequently, policies of institutional review boards require parental consent to interview children.  Unable to obtain that consent easily, creel clerks would only interview the 35-year-old anglers.  It is highly probable that the differences in transport means (bicycle and automobile), fishing platform (bank and boat), and age will produce differences in time spent fishing, the species caught, and the numbers of fish caught and harvested between the two angler groups.  Unfortunately, the interview protocol would only allow assessment of the 35-year-old group.  If the intended sampling frame was the entire urban fishery, then there likely exists a non-response bias in the survey outputs that cannot be accounted.  If, however, the intended sampling frame was only adults fishing the urban fishery, then the exclusion of the 14-year-old group does not introduce a non-response bias.  There still may be a non-response bias if a distinct portion of the 35-year-old group of anglers was not included in the interview process.

# 17.2.2 Experimental Units

	An important consideration for creel surveys is the units of interest.  For example, interview data can be collected for an individual person, for a fishing party (i.e., group of individuals that travel together for purpose of fishing), or for a household (i.e., group of people that dwell in the same residence).  Likewise, fishing effort can be reported in hours, days, or trips (which often comprise single- and multiple-day trips).  Further, anglers in the USA generally report lengths of released fish using the English system (inches), whereas biologists generally collect lengths of harvested fish using the Metric system (millimeters); thus, assessments of total catch (released \+ harvested) by size groups are limited in level of precision to 25 millimeters (1 inch \= 25 millimeters).  Unfortunately, there is no simple conversion among these units, and thus, comparison among assessments completed with different units is difficult (Box 17.2).   A standard experimental unit for creel (and angler) surveys would eliminate this confusion; however, pertinent research questions dictate that different experimental units be used in different assessments.  As such, no creel survey can gather appropriate information to address all research and management questions.  Care must be exercised when gathering data, assessing data, and interpreting data from creel surveys (Table 17.3).

	There are several important topics to consider when collecting data for creel surveys, including quality assurance of data (process oriented; focus is on prevention of inaccurate, incomplete, and inconsistent data \[e.g., dirty data\] from being collected and entered into a database), quality control of data (product oriented; focus is on identification of dirty data), and security of data (short- and long-term storage of data plus access of data for assessments).  Data management plans are formal documents designed to help researchers consider needs throughout the project for each of these important topics (see Chapter 1 for further discussion).  A general-purpose database-management system (e.g., MSSQL, MySQL, PostgreSQL) allows the definition, creation, querying, update, and administration of databases.  A database is not generally portable across different database-management systems; thus, care and foresight are required when developing a database for maximum utility.  Database structure (flat file \[has no internal hierarchy\] versus database \[has a defined internal hierarchy\]) plays a key role in each of these topics.

# 17.3 COMPONENTS OF CREEL SURVEYS

Creel surveys comprise two separate, yet linked, processes: gathering information on fishing pressure (usually assessed by counting people or boats) and gathering information on catch (usually assessed by interviewing people) (Figure 17.1).  Approaches for counts are instantaneous and progressive.  Approaches for angler interviews are access point, roving, hybrid, and postcard.  Thus, there are many combinations available for completing creel surveys (Table 17.4); the combination used should be explicitly stated (unfortunately, this oversight is prevalent in scientific literature on creel surveys).

# 17.3.1 Gathering Information on Fishing Pressure

# 17.3.1.1 On-site Assessment of Fishing Effort – Counts

Angler counts are the key unit of information because counts are used to make estimates of fishing pressure and catch (Pollock et al. 1994).  The instantaneous count is theoretically a count of all anglers at an instant point in time for a given waterbody and a given time interval (Neuhold and Lu 1957; Lambou 1961; Malvestuto 1996).  It is only possible to obtain an instantaneous count on smaller waterbodies with unobstructed views.  On most waterbodies, a clerk must quickly move between vantage points (i.e., rove) to count all anglers within a short period; this functionally serves as an instantaneous count if no anglers entered or exited the fishery (Hoenig et al. 1993).  During this count period, the clerk does not interview anglers.  Times of instantaneous counts within a period should be random (often stratified random, with stratification across times, days, and seasons that are hypothesized to differ in effort) because extrapolation occurs to the entire period.

The progressive count is a summation of instantaneous counts for subareas of a waterbody that are made as a clerk travels a predefined circuit around a waterbody (Hoenig et al. 1993).  The progressive count is useful when a clerk is unable to traverse multiple spots within a short period (\<1 hour) to see the entire waterbody.  The progressive count is necessary when it is likely that anglers are entering or leaving the waterbody during a count.  Again, the clerk does not interview anglers during the count period.  Starting location along the circuit and direction of travel (clockwise or counterclockwise) should be random.

The bus route is a modification to the progressive count that allows interviews to be completed while the clerk is traversing around the circuit (McGlennon and Kinlock 1997).  In this case, the clerk completes counts and angler interviews at each survey area along the circuit.  Likewise, starting location along the circuit and direction of travel (clockwise or counterclockwise) should be random.  Duration spent at each survey area should be predetermined and should be constant across survey areas (to simplify calculations).

The aerial count can be used for instantaneous counts or progressive counts, and is advantageous for extremely large areas (e.g., oceans and large lakes) that are not easily traversed by vehicle or boat (Fraidenburg and Bargmann 1982; Vølstad et al. 2006).  Aerial counts can be either instantaneous or progressive, depending on the size of the area covered.  However, unlike instantaneous and progressive counts, nonrandom sampling often is not feasible due to pilot and plane availability, restrictive flight path options, and weather conditions that may prevent flight or impair visibility (Askey et al. 2018).  Furthermore, sample size is often limited by cost of aircraft operation.  An important consideration of aerial counts is treatment of boats in transit, which determines whether one will ultimately estimate “on-the-water” pressure or “active-fishing” pressure (Soupir et al. 2006).  The difficulty with boats in transit is determining the recreational activity of the individuals on-board (i.e., whether they are fishing or participating in some other water-based recreational activity \[e.g., cruising, sunbathing, or water skiing\]).

# 17.3.1.2 Remote Assessment of Fishing Effort – Counts

High frequency on-site creel surveys are an excellent method to assess within day, daily, and seasonal temporal patterns in fishing activity and total effort, but they require substantial labor resources.  The level of labor resources required often precludes the application of high frequency surveys to large-scale recreational fisheries distributed along coastlines in marine systems, or across broad landscapes of rivers and large lakes in freshwater systems.  Remote assessment methods, with substantially lower per site costs, can be used to assess fishing effort across large-scale fisheries.  Aerial boat counts and remote cameras have both been used to assess fishing effort in a diversity of marine and freshwater fisheries, but their application methodology and data must be carefully assessed to ensure precision and accuracy of total effort estimates.

Aerial surveys of fishing activity have been used to assess spatial and temporal patterns in fishing effort at least since the late 1970s in North America (Parkinson et al. 1988; Vølstad et al. 2006; Tinsman and Whitmore 2006; Askey et al. 2018), Australia (Smallwood 2012), and Europe (Veiga et al. 2010).  This method is best used in fisheries where anglers are mobile, spatial scales are large, access is remote, and the purpose is to assess fishing effort over broad spatial and temporal scales.  Use of aircraft to monitor fishing activity provides instantaneous counts that are typically not random in space or time due to constraints in coordinating sites along flight paths, scheduling aircraft timetables and weather constraints (Askey et al. 2018).  Clearly, as airtime is expensive, observations are most efficiently made along flightpaths of relatively nearby fisheries. Recent experience in the use of aerial boat counts in recreational fisheries in British Columbia, Canada, suggest that per lake, the annual cost varied from CAD$179, where lakes were geographically close and charters less expensive, to CAD$635 for more remote lakes where flights were more expensive (Greenberg and Godin 2015).  Inflation factors can be applied to extrapolate from instantaneous counts to the scales of days, weeks, seasons, or years. The accuracy of instantaneous counts as proxies of total effort is maximized by making the counts at peak fishing times.  If the typical duration of trips and patterns in fishing effort within and among days has been quantified, instantaneous counts can be extrapolated to estimate total fishing effort.  These inflation factors are most effectively determined with high resolution ancillary data collected at finer time scales because there is typically substantial temporal variability within days (e.g., dawn, day, dusk, night), among days (e.g., weekdays, weekends and holidays), among fishing seasons (e.g., spring, summer, autumn, winter) and across recreational fish species (e.g., black crappie, largemouth bass, walleye, white bass) (Askey et al. 2018).

Remote cameras, in contrast to aerial boat counts, can provide high temporal resolution of patterns in fishing effort.  Remote cameras have been used as activity counters at access points and boat launches (Hartill et al 2016\) and as direct counts of boats during fishing activity (Greenberg and Godin 2015; van Poorten et al. 2015).  They can be web based with Wi-Fi or satellite data transmission (Hartill et al. 2016\) or locally saved and stored images for subsequent intermittent downloads (Greenberg and Godin 2015).  Relatively inexpensive time-lapse remote field cameras can be strategically placed to capture fishing activity for a subsample of an individual fishery and placed in networks of cameras to capture activity over broad landscapes.  Understanding the field of vision of each camera and the generally non-random placement of cameras is key in developing unbiased estimates of fishing effort (van Poorten et al. 2015).  The field of view of a camera defines the shape of the image of fishers on lakes, streams, or nearshore marine systems and most often only represents a subsample of the whole area involved in a fishery, resulting in missing data that have to be estimated.  Estimation of effort for the whole fishery requires a conversion factor from the subsample represented by the camera field of view image (van Poorten et al. 2015).  It is necessary to independently convert field of view counts with intermittent whole fishery counts because the camera placement is typically strategically placed to be both accessible and to sample as large an area as possible within distance and resolution constraints.  Conversion can be done with lower frequency instantaneous whole-system counts on site or by aerial counts.  Yet, conversion adds uncertainty due to the high frequency of zero counts typically observed in subsamples that must be accounted.  A second source of missing data is due to camera malfunction or vandalism (van Poorten et al. 2015; Hartill et al. 2016).  Quantitative methods to impute total fishing effort from camera images given the presence of these two types of missing data have been developed by van Poorten et al. (2015).    

An important constraint on the use of high-resolution cameras to estimate fishing effort is the task of image analysis.  Collection of images from a network of cameras over seasons and years results in a huge catalogue of images.  Effective and efficient protocols for extracting effort estimates requires the use of image processing software, but it is not clear how much can be automated, and what requires human interpretation (Greenberg and Godin 2015; Hartill et al. 2016).  Efficiencies can be attained in the image analysis process by automating as much as possible the import, cataloguing, viewing, interpretation, data capture, validation, error filtering and analysis tasks (Greenberg and Godin 2015).  Technician time for this process was estimated to cost about CAD$500 per site, for images collected hourly for an open water temperate zone fishing season (Greenberg and Godin 2015).     

# 17.3.2 Gathering Information on Catch – Angler Interviews

Angler interviews can occur at access points (e.g., boat ramps, docks, and parking areas), along the shoreline (bank), or on the water from a boat.  Angler interviews are classified according to the method through which the clerk intercepts anglers for interviews.  For access point, the clerk administers interviews at locations where anglers gain entry to waterbodies.  In general, access-point interviews contain fishing information for the party for the entirety of the day (i.e., completed trips) because anglers are intercepted while egressing waterbodies.  For roving, the clerk administers interviews at locations where anglers are actively fishing.  Movement of the clerk through the survey area can be random or a defined pattern.  In general, roving interviews contain fishing information for the party for a portion of the day (i.e., incomplete trips).  For hybrid, the clerk administers interviews at both locations where anglers egress and at locations were anglers are actively fishing.  For postcard, the clerk delivers surveys on windshields of parked vehicles at locations where anglers gain entry to waterbodies.

# 17.4 CREEL SURVEY DESIGN

The purpose of creel survey design is to produce accurate and precise estimates of some desired component of angler activity.  Unfortunately, assessment of accuracy is difficult (but see Pierce and Bindman 1994; Newman et al. 1997).  Conversely, assessment of precision is relatively easy when replication of sampling units exists.  We prescribe to a philosophy that all estimates must be accompanied by some measure of variation (e.g., variance, standard error, and 95% confidence interval).  Of course, the variance is influenced by survey design.

The precision of angler effort estimates based on instantaneous counts is affected by sampling variance among days and sampling variance within days (Newman et al. 1997).  The ratio of these two sampling variances can help determine the optimal number of instantaneous counts within a day and optimal number of days within a month (or month-day type stratum) to sample for a specified precision (Newman et al. 1997).  Further, small sample size (few interviews) may lead to large variance and poor confidence-interval coverage for harvest rate estimates (Newman et al. 1997).

# 17.4.1 Strata Design

Dividing time and space into smaller segments minimizes variance estimates when the segments correspond to biological phenomena that produce relatively large (e.g., an order of magnitude) differences in effort or catch among the segments.  Dividing time and space into smaller, more manageable segments also simplifies creel sampling by reducing the size of units for logistical reasons.  Creel surveys are often temporally stratified by years and months.  The year stratum generally corresponds with fiscal years of license and permit sales and facilitates comparisons among years with various economic indicators or years with different weather patterns (e.g., wet-dry cycles).  The month strata generally correspond to a calendar month and facilitates hiring of clerks.  The month strata also allow the investigator to bin seasonal changes in fish biology and ecology that often affect catch rates, and hence angler participation.  Historically, days for creel surveys were stratified into week and weekend days with holidays included in the weekend-day strata.  This stratification is justified by social norms of work and school days occurring on weekdays (Monday-Friday) and non-work and non-school days occurring on weekend days (Saturday-Sunday); we do note that social norms of work and school days are evolving, especially with many business operating seven days a week (some even 24 hours per day) and with many extracurricular activities occurring on weekends.

	It is unfeasible to complete on-site counts and interviews on all days in a fishing season; thus, we evoke a technique called subsampling (Cochran 1977\) in which we randomly select days within strata for completing on-site counts and interviews.  We further evoke a technique historically called *two-stage sampling* (Cochran 1977\) because our random sampling design for interviews within stratum is determined in two steps or stages, with the first stage being day and the second stage being shift (period) within the day.  Rasmussen et al. (1998) correctly noted that the sampling design historically used for creel surveys is actually three-stage sampling, with the third stage being count time within the shift (a two-stage survey design with count times as the second stage would require that count times be randomly selected from the entire day).  Each stage contains its own component of variance, and variances among stages are summed to produce the variance of the stratum (Cochran 1977).

Given limited computing capabilities of the past and a lack of application of sampling theory, the general approach for assessment was to generate estimates for an “average day of a month” based on weighted means of data from week and weekend days, which was extrapolated to an entire month by multiplying the “average day” by the number of days in the month (Malvestuto 1996).  Given current computing capabilities, the contemporary approach for assessment (Figure 17.2) is to generate mean and variance estimates for days in each of the strata.  These estimates are extrapolated to the strata within a month (i.e., weekdays in a month and weekend days in a month) and then summed across strata (i.e., weekdays in month \+ weekend days in a month) to obtain a monthly estimate.  In addition, the contemporary approach also includes a third strata, high-use days, where pressure is generally several orders of magnitude greater than typical weekend days within a respective month (Pope et al. 2017).  In the USA, labor-day weekend, memorial-day weekend, and Fourth-of-July weekend are examples of high-use days; large fishing tournaments and other special events may also create high-use days.

At least two samples (measures) are needed within a stratum to obtain an estimate of variance.  Thus, a minimum of two days sampling are needed for each weekday and weekend day within a given month; similarly, a minimum of two sampling days are needed for each stratum of high-use days, which may or may not be confined to a single month.  Malvestuto (1996) suggested that an optimal sampling design was achieved by allocating sampling effort among weekdays and weekend days proportionally to total fishing effort expended in each stratum, which requires knowledge (usually gained from prior data) of fishing effort for a waterbody.  However, choice of sampling design, like fishery management action, always involves tradeoffs; careful thought and consideration are needed to understand the influences of sampling decisions on creel data quality and outputs.  Limited sampling effort during low-use periods may result in missing information needed to represent the fishery, and importantly affect data analyses.  For example, consider a reservoir where 90 percent of fishing effort occurs from boats on weekends.  If we sample nine weekend days and one weekday per month (difficult to do given that most months only have eight weekend days), there is a high probability that we would not interview an angler party on a week day that fished from the bank, which becomes a problem if we counted any anglers fishing from the bank on that week day because we have weekday effort data without weekday catch data (catch rate \= NA) for extrapolation of estimates.  We generally increase sampling effort during periods of low use because we place a premium on estimates of variance, which cannot be estimated from missing data.  Common temporal strata that one might want to track variance are within year (or fishing season), within month, within week, and within day.  As always, your research question should dictate which strata are needed for tracking variance.  For example, a temporal stratum might be two days following a put-and-take stocking event (Harmon et al. 2018).

	In addition to temporal stratification, surveys can be stratified by space.  Spatial stratification is necessary when systems are sufficiently large as to prevent complete coverage by a single clerk.  Spatial stratification is also beneficial when working on areas with distinct habitats (e.g., Lewis and Clark Reservoir, Nebraska-South Dakota, which has a large delta at its upper end) or multiple waterbodies, especially when fish assemblages or angler groups differ among habitats or waterbodies (e.g., Chizinski et al. 2014).

# 17.4.2 Heterogeneous Population of Anglers

	Though all anglers are unique, there tend to be groups into which anglers can be binned.  Segmentation (Tynan and Drayton 1987\) or typology (Connelly et al. 2001; Oh et al. 2005; Morey et al. 2006\) is the division of the angler population into subgroups.  There are numerous ways to segment markets (Tynan and Drayton 1987); four basic types of segmentation are geographic, demographic, psychographic, and behavioral.  Geographic segmentation uses defined geographic boundaries for separating individuals into groups, usually based on home residence or waterbody being fished.  Demographic segmentation uses defined ranges in variables, such as age, sex, education level, and household income, often in a multivariate approach, for separating individuals into groups.  Psychographic segmentation uses defined traits, such as values, personalities, motivators and lifestyles, for separating individuals into groups.  Behavioral segmentation uses defined decision-making processes for separating individuals into groups.  Historically, one of the most common segmentations of anglers is behavioral, based on the method (e.g., bank, boat) from which anglers actively fish.  More recently, there has been a move towards more detailed behavioral segmentation based on willingness to travel, propensity to harvest, site-choice characteristics, annual effort, and gear-type used (e.g., Ward et al. 2013; Dabrowska et al. 2017).

For creel surveys, anglers are frequently segmented based on variables such as age, gender, household income, preferred method of accessing a fishery (i.e., fishing from the bank versus fishing from a boat), species targeted on a given day, and frequency of participation in recreational fishing.  Segmentation is an important strategy that facilitates angler surveys and helps quantify non-response bias.  Segmentation is generally an inherent component of survey designs (discussed below).  Segmentation is also important for marketing fishing opportunities to prospective anglers.

The research question always dictates the survey (experimental) approach and analytical interpretations.  Consideration of segmentations helps minimize variance estimates and facilitates analytical interpretations.  For example, “what is total effort of fishing on Lake Halleck, Nebraska (a 1.6-ha reservoir in the Omaha metropolitan area without a boat ramp)?” dictates that anglers be counted at random times, preferably within day-type strata to reduce overall variance.  The absence of a boat ramp perhaps suggests that anglers would be segmented into a single group based on behavior (i.e., bank anglers); thus, segmentation could be ignored in this survey.  Even if many anglers accessed Lake Halleck with kayaks, segmentation could still be ignored without introducing bias for the estimate of total effort.  However, ignoring segmentation in this example would preclude additional insights about which segment, boat or bank, of anglers comprises the greatest proportion of total effort.

Recreational fishing patterns (e.g., daily, seasonally, annually) affect encounter rates (detectability) of clerks with anglers.  If fishing patterns differ among angler segments, then detection probabilities are likely to differ among angler segments within many of the strata sampled.  If the sampling design incorporates segmentation of anglers in a manner that aligns with the angler segments that have different fishing patterns, then estimates of total effort, total catch and total harvest should be unbiased.  However, if the sampling design does not correctly incorporate segmentation of anglers, then estimates of total effort, total catch, and total harvest will likely be biased in an unknown direction.  Thus, correctly accounting for angler heterogeneity in sampling design is important.

# 17.5 CREEL SURVEY ANALYSES

# 17.5.1 Effort

The most influential parameters calculated from creel surveys are total effort estimates.  Total effort or extrapolated angler effort, based on counts of anglers at a waterbody, is the estimate of the angler-hours expended at a waterbody given a specific time interval. Estimates important to fisheries managers (e.g., catch, harvest, release) are all calculated using the estimated total angler effort.  Thus, it is important to choose carefully the type of effort method and strata design to ensure accuracy and precision of the total effort estimates.

	Fishing pressure for a time interval is estimated by multiplying the average of the counts of anglers by the duration (hours) of time interval.  This seems counterintuitive to some who want to multiply the count of anglers incorrectly by the average time that parties spent fishing on said day.  It is important to also note that counts are estimates of effort (hours), not angler trips (Hoening et al. 1993).

	It is advisable to have multiple counts during a creel shift; counts separated by ≥ 1 hour are generally required for logistical reasons.

	Another approach to calculate effort is the progressive count (Box 18.3), which attempts to count all the bank and boat anglers on a waterbody within a relatively longer timeframe than the instantaneous count.  This method is particularly useful on large waterbodies or waterbodies with many coves that make it difficult to count anglers from vantage points.  The progressive count method requires: 1\) route that covers the entire area of the lake, 2\) starting location along route is chosen at random, 3\) direction of travel along route is randomly determined among the alternatives (often clockwise and counterclockwise), and 4\) travel along route is at a constant speed and faster than movements by anglers on the waterbody.  The creel clerk keeps a running tally of the unique anglers observed en route.  The progressive count provides an unbiased estimate of effort if the count follows the four requirements specified above (see Robson \[1961\] for the proof).

	A modification to the progressive count is the bus route (Robson and Jones 1989, Jones et al. 1990, Jones and Robson 1991).  The bus route method (Box 18.3) was designed to cover multiple access points across a broad geographic area, such that it would be difficult to sample all sites with equal selection probabilities during a single creel-sampling day.  Using this method, effort is calculated in one of two ways: 1\) the time-interval count of angler vehicles or boat trailers or 2\) expansion from completed trip interviews.  The time-interval method should be used in areas where there is low effort, few interviews are expected (probability of intercepting an angler coming off the water is low), and there is limited use by non-fishing boats.


# 17.5.2 Catch

  The importance of catch parameters calculated from creel surveys is illustrated in its name—creel.  Biologists frequently use catch parameters for recommending fishing regulations and fish stockings.  Catch is measured at either the individual level or the party level, and then total catch is extrapolated by multiplying the average catch rate by the total effort; thus, merging both components (interviews and counts) of creel surveys.

In general, access-point interviews comprise complete information about the days fishing for each party (though one must be careful to inquire, as some parties may depart a waterbody with intentions of returning later that day), whereas roving interviews comprise incomplete information about the days fishing for each party.  A hybrid approach to interviews may be employed when clerks are confined to the shoreline or when clerks are using a bus route for counts; this approach may produce complete information for anglers fishing from boats and incomplete information for anglers fishing from the shoreline.  Postcard interviews are generally assumed to comprise complete information about the days fishing for each party.

One of the challenges for interviewing anglers is intercepting them at appropriate times.  Waiting for anglers to exit a waterbody provides the most complete information about the days fishing events because anglers have finished fishing for the day, yet it can be extremely difficult to gather a sufficient sample size when most anglers exit at a similar time such as when bad weather or park closures force anglers off the waterbody.  Intercepting anglers on the waterbody while they are engaged in fishing often provides more interviews, but less complete information is gathered about the days fishing events because anglers are still fishing.  Furthermore, anglers that fish for a long time are more likely to be intercepted by a roving clerk than anglers that fish for a short time (Hoenig et al. 1997).  This can provide biased estimates of catch rates if catch influences time spent fishing.  For example, an angling party may fish extended hours if the party is catching many fish.  In this event, the greater likelihood of intercepting and recording higher catch rates is not indicative of all angler parties that fished on this day.  Similarly, interviewing an angler party that just began (\<15 minutes) fishing and caught a fish will generally produce an extremely large (outlier) catch rate estimate (Hoening et al. 1997\) that also is not indicative of all angler parties that fished on this day.  As such, Hoening et al. (1997) recommended that interviews for parties that have not completed their fishing for the day be confined to parties that have fished at least 0.5 hours.

Biologists are often interested in the catch rate for anglers targeting a specific species (e.g., walleye).  A species-targeting catch rate provides insight into a fish population of interest and is thought to be more informative than the overall catch rate for a species by all anglers because zero catch rates by anglers purposefully avoiding a species (e.g., anglers targeting channel catfish) are excluded from assessment.  It is tempting to estimate the total number of fish (e.g., walleye) caught by anglers targeting that species (e.g., walleye-seeking anglers); however, there is generally no way to know during a count of anglers which parties are targeting which species and thus, there is no associated total effort for species-seeking anglers.

Once an angler catches a fish, the angler must then decide the fate (i.e., released or harvested) of the fish.  Harvest and total harvest are calculated exactly as catch and total catch, respectively, except that the “catch rate” used in these calculations is for the portion of catch that is harvested (i.e., harvest rate).  Thus, catch rate and harvest rate are by definition correlated.

# 17.5.3 Integrated Assessments of Total Effort and Total Catch

A primary goal of the human dimensions of recreational fisheries assessments is to estimate fishing effort and catch. On-site creel and aerial and remote camera activity counts are all useful in accomplishing this goal. Each approach has strengths and weaknesses (as discussed previously), but it is in combination that we are likely to maximize the accuracy and precision of effort and catch estimation (Figure 17.3).

Aerial surveys provide instantaneous counts of fishing activity over broad landscapes of fisheries, focusing on high effort within day and weekday, weekend and holiday strata. Remote cameras collect data on within day effort distributions. The subsample attribute of the camera data can be expanded with intermittent whole system counts provided by aerial surveys. Therefore, in combination the aerial and camera assessments can yield total fishing effort at the daily, seasonal, and annual time scales. When combined with catch and trip-length data from on-site creel surveys, total catch can be estimated from daily catch rate and daily effort at time scales from days to years.

Integrated analyses of this type have been developed for several large-scale recreational fisheries, often using a pair of the approaches (outlined in Figure 17.3). The combination of aerial fishing activity counts and on-site creel is most common and has been used in a diversity of marine and freshwater fisheries to estimate total effort and total catch (Parkinson et al. 1988; Soupir et al. 2006; Vølstad et al. 2006; Smucker et al. 2010; Hartill et al. 2011). This approach can be used to estimate spatial patterns in effort, catch, and harvest at hourly, daily, and annual time scales, with explicit levels of uncertainty in the estimates. But other combinations, aerial and resolution cameras (Askey et al. 2018), cameras and creel (van Poorten et al. 2015), and all three- aerial, cameras, and creel (Smallwood et al. 2012\) have provided estimates of effort, catch and levels of uncertainty for a diversity of recreational fisheries.

In aggregate, this series of studies that have combined approaches to estimating effort and catch, have identified a series of strategic recommendations for the design of future studies. First, designs can be improved by incorporating multiple sources of effort data. Several modelling approaches, including Hierarchical Bayesian (van Poorten et al 2015), General Linear Models (Hartill et al. 2016), and General Linear Mixed Models (Lancaster et al 2017; Askey et al. 2018\) have been used to incorporate data sources varying in scope and scale and effectively assess uncertainty in estimates. Complementary data can improve the accuracy of effort estimates and the efficiency of effort monitoring programs (Askey et al. 2018). The most effective designs are stratified to target high effort strata in combination with complimentary high-resolution temporal sampling for expansion over broad spatial landscapes of fisheries. In this way, recreational fishery resource managers can most effectively monitor their fisheries and estimate fishing mortality rates as key performance indicators.

# 17.5.4 Technological Advancements for Passive Indices of Effort and Catch

Technology creates new possibilities and alters the mix of choices (Mesthene 1968\) we have for assessing fishing effort and catch.  Drones (Schiffman 2014), time-lapse and motion-detection cameras (Kucera and Barrett 2011), and visitor (people or vehicles) counters (Cessford et al. 2002\) offer possibilities for continuous collection of effort data without the need for constant on-site clerks.  Angler apps (Venturelli et al. 2017), web crawlers (Dhenakaran and Thirugnana Sambanthan 2011; Wilde and Pope 2013), and social networks (Scott 1988\) offer opportunities to gather information directly from “diaries” of individual anglers.

Another approach involving technology involves random-stratified designs using email and internet surveys. For example, Dabrowska et al. (2017) and Carruthers et al. (2019) used fishing license databases with emails to design a random-stratified (by geographic location) design to assess fishing effort and stated behavior. The email invited participation in the survey and the survey was completed over the internet. A big advantage of this is the broad geographic coverage and large sample sizes – in the thousands to tens of thousands. The investment is upfront survey design and web costs.

Technology is exciting, with constant advancements and many new potential applications.  However, though technology can make some processes more effective and efficient, it can come with challenges.  For example, many agencies are having difficulty with long-term surveys where the sampling frame was households determined by telephone landlines.  Current practices with cellular telephones, specifically the ability to maintain a telephone number that is not spatially georeferenced (i.e., area code has little meaning on cellular numbers about residence location), and the elimination of landlines from many households makes it difficult to create a sampling frame of telephone numbers for people living in distinct areas (Lepkowski et al. 2008).  Undoubtedly, technological advances will continue to create challenges for gathering long-term data sets that were started by well-intentioned scientists.

# 17.6 EMERGING APPLICATIONS

Creel surveys have come a long way from the original wicker basket estimates of angler harvest.  New and emerging ways to conduct creel surveys and use their data are changing the landscape of recreational fisheries management.  For instance, network theory is the study of graphs as representation of relationships among discrete objects; that is, one can graph a network, such as that of a population of anglers, by connecting objects (nodes or vertices) with lines (edges).   The visual representation of interrelationships among objects provides opportunity for greater insights and understanding of complexities of recreational fisheries, especially useful for developing and conveying conceptual models of anglers.  As an example, Martin et al. (2017) used network theory to gain insights about substitute waterbodies within a regional fishery, and Chizinski et al. (2018) used network theory to gain insights about which fish species co-occurred in catch and harvest of various target-seeking groups of anglers.

In an ever-expanding era of “big data,” there are opportunities to build across existing datasets to address broader scale questions (Hampton et al. 2013).  For creel survey data, crosswalking information between state agencies and fishery-independent data can help address transboundary research questions and even help address data gaps for regions with limited resources (Midway et al. 2016).  These applications do not come without major hurdles (e.g., data sharing, staff time, privacy issues), but regional and national coordination efforts can help address these concerns.  These novel approaches do require significant investment but can reap major rewards in terms of improving our understanding of angler effort, ultimately helping us ensure sustainable management of these important fisheries resources.

Most data discussed in other chapters throughout this book can be collected via assistance from anglers (i.e., participatory science programs) — that is, creel surveys can serve as surrogate biology.  Angler surveys (including creel surveys, tournament data reporting, angler diaries, telephone surveys, and mail surveys) are often used as alternatives or complements to conventional data collection methods (De Jesus et al. 2009).  Creel surveys have been used to assess catch rates of fish, a surrogate to population density (Gabelhouse and Willis 1986), catch rates of trophy fish, a surrogate to production of large and rare fish (De Jesus et al. 2009), sex and reproductive characteristics of fish harvested, a surrogate to life-history characteristics of the fish population (Kearns et al. 2016), age and size structures of fish harvested, surrogates to age and size structures of the fish population (Weiss-Glanz and Stanley 1984; Ebbers 1987), stomach contents of captured fish, a surrogate to diets of the fish population (Stables et al. 1990), and condition (mass-length relationships) of harvested fish, a surrogate to condition of individual fish in the population (He et al. 2008).  Creel surveys also provide opportunities for landscape ecology (e.g., Kaemingk et al. 2018). Even so, caution on use of creel surveys for any assessment, including surrogate biology, is always warranted (Shuter et al. 1987; Novinger 1990; Roach et al. 1999; Bray and Schramm 2001).  There is no perfect sampling design or scheme; choice of sampling design is generally determined through consideration of pros and cons of the data collected within the logistical constraints provided.  Creel surveys for surrogate biology are directly affected by where and how anglers go fishing within and across seasons throughout a year.

Table 17.1.  Definitions of terms commonly used during creel surveys.

| Term | Definition |
| ----- | ----- |
| access-point interviews | On-site interviews of anglers that occur at locations where anglers gain entry to waterbodies |
| aerial count | A count of anglers (may be instantaneous or progressive) that is made from an aircraft during flight |
| angler survey | Systematic, scientific approach to gathering and assessing data from anglers about recreational-fishing activities and desires  |
| bus-route count | A modification to the progressive count that allows interviews to be completed while the clerk is traversing around the circuit |
| catch | Number of fish captured (harvested \+ released) by an angler or party for a given day collected at the interview level |
| clerk | Trained professional that collects data from anglers |
| count | On-site enumeration of anglers actively fishing |
| creel survey | Angler surveys that are completed on-site and often comprised of two components:  counts of anglers and in-person interviews of anglers |
| design | Logistical and analytical framework that guides data collection and analyses; it is specific to the research question |
| effort | Duration (hours) of fishing for an angler or party for a given day collected at the interview level |
| harvest | Number of fish captured and retained (kept) by an angler or party for a given day collected at the interview level |
| hybrid interviews | On-site interviews of anglers that is a mixture of access-point and roving interviews completed within the same creel survey; generally, this involves assess-point interviews for boat anglers and roving interviews for bank anglers |
| instantaneous count | A count of all anglers at an instant point in time for a given waterbody and a given time interval |
| interview | On-site gathering of data by a clerk |
| party | Group of anglers that fish together often included in a single interview |
| postcard interviews | On-site distribution of surveys on windshields of parked vehicles at locations where anglers gain entry to waterbodies; surveys are generally completed by anglers off-site |
| pressure | *See* total effort *and* effort |
| progressive count | A summation of instantaneous counts for subareas of a waterbody that are made as a clerk travels a predefined circuit around a waterbody |
| release | Number of fish captured and released by an angler or party for a given day collected at the interview level |
| research question | Central issue that determines design and analyses decisions |
| roving interviews | On-site interviews of anglers that occur at locations where anglers are actively fishing |
| shift | Duration within a given day during which a clerk is on-site for the purpose of counting and interviewing anglers |
| species targeted | Primary fish species desired or sought to be captured by an angler or party for a given day |
| strata | Hierarchical blocks of sampling units; examples of strata include year, season, month, angler type, period, and other temporal and spatial variables associate with the research question |
| total catch | Extrapolated estimate of catch for a given waterbody and period |
| total effort | Extrapolated estimate of effort for a given waterbody and period \[note:  “pressure” and “total effort” are often used interchangeably in fishery literature\] |
| total harvest | Extrapolated estimate of harvest for a given waterbody and period |
| total release | Extrapolated estimate of release for a given waterbody and period |
|  |  |

Table 17.3.  Ten common and ubiquitous mistakes to avoid when developing and analyzing a creel survey.

| Mistake | Influence on Creel Estimates |
| ----- | ----- |
| Skipping zeros for counts or catches | Overestimates total effort, total catch, and total harvest |
| Targeting successful parties (e.g., interviews at fish-cleaning stations) | Overestimates catch and harvest rates, and overestimates total catch and total harvest |
| Tendency to measure biggest fish in subsamples of harvested fish | Overestimates size structure of harvested fish |
| Counts not covering entire waterbody | Unrepresentative sample creates unknown bias in estimates |
| Interviews not covering entire waterbody or not including all groups of individuals (e.g., excluding non-English speaking anglers) | Unrepresentative sample creates unknown bias in estimates |
| Mixing units of measures (e.g., some fish measured in inches and others measured in mm) or mixing levels of precision for measurements | Variability in precision creates unknown bias in estimates |
| Species misidentification by anglers | Creates unknown bias, especially if rate of misidentification is unknown, in estimates |
| Over or under estimation of party-level effort (e.g., not realizing that a party of 4 anglers included 2 anglers that fished 4 hours and 2 anglers that fished 1 hour) | Under or overestimates catch and harvest rates, which translates to under or over estimates of total catch and total harvest |
| Lack of standardized training of creel clerks | Potential loss of data |
| Failure to follow quality assurance-quality control (QA-QC) protocols (e.g., not using error-checking procedures at multiple stages) | Inaccurate data creates unknown bias in estimates |

# Box 17.1 Generating a stratified-random creel schedule

Let us consider a single launch site with a parking area for boaters to access a river. We wish to estimate angling pressure on this river from this single launch site. We know from prior investigation that all boaters using this launch do so for the purpose of fishing. We also know that use of this launch site is often an order of magnitude greater on weekend days than weekdays, and that there is seasonality in this fishery. Thus, we decide to conduct an assessment of fishing pressure by instantaneous counts of boat-trailers in the parking lot during April-October with sampling effort stratified by month and day type (weekend, week).

*Load libraries: tidyverse and lubridate.*

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)

*Generating a sequence of dates that represent the creel sampling period*

calendar \<- tibble(date \= seq(ymd("2019-04-01"), ymd("2019-10-31"), by \= "1 day")) \# create a sequence of dates

calendar %\>%
  mutate(month \= month(date, label \= TRUE), \#label months
         dayWeek \= wday(date,label \= TRUE), \#label day of week
         strata \= ifelse(dayWeek %in% c("Sat","Sun"),"weekend day","weekday"),  \# determine if day of the week is a weekend day or weekday
         group \= 1\) %\>%  \# group 1 for all
  expand\_grid(shift= c("morning","afternoon")) \-\> calendarFull \# expamnd to have both morning and afternoon shifts

*Define how you treat holidays or other high-use days.* There is the potential that some high-use periods (labor day weekend) that can span across a month. To address this, and keep the estimates within those periods and not split across months, we use **group**, which is just a way of identifying those different high-use periods across creel sampling year. For the below example, we are going to treat holidays in with the “weekend day” strata.

*Randomly sampling dates from the full calendar using the purrr package (part of tidyverse).* For the below example, we are going to sample 6 weekend days and 10 week days in a month. Further, we are going to equally split the number of morning shifts and afternoon shifts for each of the strata. Setting the seed, ensures that we will get the same random selection of days.

set.seed(1234) \# set random seed
numWeekends \= 6
numWeekdays \= 10

\# sample morning shift
calendarFull %\>%
  filter(shift \== "morning" ) %\>% \# filter out just mornings
  group\_by(month, strata,group, shift) %\>% \# group data
  nest() %\>% \# nest the days to sample by grouping data
  mutate(daystoSample \= ifelse(strata \== "weekend day",numWeekends/2,numWeekdays/2)) %\>% \# dividing by two, for mornign shift
  mutate(sampledDays \=  map2(data, daystoSample, sample\_n)) %\>% \# sample nested data
  select(month, shift, sampledDays, group, strata) %\>% \# select columns
  unnest(sampledDays) %\>% \# unnest the data
  ungroup() %\>% \# remove grouping
  select(date, month, dayWeek, shift, group, strata) %\>%
  mutate(month \= as.character(month)) \-\> CreelSchedule\_morning \# convert month to a character

\# sample afternoon shifts (annotations similar as above)
calendarFull %\>%
  filter(shift \== "afternoon", \# filter out just afternoons
         \!date %in% CreelSchedule\_morning$date) %\>%
  group\_by(month, strata,group, shift) %\>%
  nest() %\>%
  mutate(daystoSample \= ifelse(strata \== "weekend day",numWeekends/2,numWeekdays/2)) %\>% \# dividing by two, for afternoon shift
  mutate(sampledDays \=  map2(data, daystoSample, sample\_n)) %\>%
  select(month, shift, sampledDays, group, strata) %\>%
  unnest(sampledDays) %\>%
  ungroup() %\>%
  select(date, month, dayWeek, shift, group, strata) %\>%
  mutate(month \= as.character(month))  \-\> CreelSchedule\_afternoon

\# combine the two into a single data frame
rbind(CreelSchedule\_morning, CreelSchedule\_afternoon) %\>%
  arrange(date) \-\> creelSchedule

*Create a function to sample count times during the creel shifts.* Generating count times during a creel shift has several complications. One, what time interval do you want to sample from (e.g., every minute, every 15 minutes)? Two, how much of a time interval do you want between counts? When having more than one count during a creel shift, requires that you remove some potential count times from the pool dependent on the time that is first selected. The easiest way to do this is using a while loop inside a function to sample your count times.

count\_times \<- **function**(nCounts=3, timeInterval=15, timeBtwn \= 60, startTime, endTime){
 seq(ymd\_hm(paste("2019-01-01",startTime)), \# create a sequence of times (NOTE: the date does not matter)
     ymd\_hm(paste("2019-01-01",endTime)),
     by \= paste(timeInterval, "min")) \-\> timePeriod

  countTimes \<- tibble(time \= mdy\_hms(rep(NA,nCounts))) \# a place to store times
   c \= 1 \# start out counter at 1
  **while**(c \<= nCounts){
    countTimes$time\[c\] \<- sample(timePeriod, 1\) \# sample one time from random times
    ind \<- which(abs(interval(timePeriod, countTimes$time\[c\]) / minutes(1)) \>= timeBtwn) \# remove times that fall with ing the time between counts
    timePeriod \<- timePeriod\[ind\]
    c \<- c \+ 1 \# advance counter
    }
  out \<- paste(format(sort(countTimes$time), "%T"), collapse \= ", ") \# collapse times into a single string
  return(out)
  }

set.seed(12345)
count\_times(startTime \= "06:00", endTime \="13:30") \# example of using the function

# Box 17.2. Difficulty of converting “experimental units” of interest.

Let us consider a hypothetical day for a small impoundment with four fishing parties that fished 4, 4, 4, and 12 hours and comprised 3, 2, 2, and 1 anglers, respectively.

If our “experimental unit” (i.e., level at which we are collected interview data) of interest is a party, then fishing effort for this hypothetical day would be 24 party-hours (undefined variance) with an average fishing time per party of 6 hours (variance \= 16\) and an average party size of 2 anglers (variance \= 0.7). Extrapolation of party information would provide an estimate of 48 hours of fishing effort (4 parties × 6 hours/party × 2 anglers/party) for this hypothetical day, but you note that the units in this extrapolation do not carry through (i.e., hours × angler/party does not equal hours)—an important indication that the extrapolation, or conversion in this case, does not jive with the actual effort of 40 hours of fishing (4 hours × 3 anglers \+ 4 hours × 2 anglers \+ 4 hours × 2 anglers \+ 12 hours × 1 angler) for this hypothetical day.

If our “experimental unit” of interest is an individual angler, then fishing effort for this hypothetical day would be 40 hours (undefined variance) with an average fishing time of 5 hours (variance \= 8\) for each of the 8 anglers. The conversion to parties is also difficult; that is, we would estimate the average time spent fishing for each party to be 5 hours compared to the actual average of 6 hours per party.

Thus, it is imperative that the level at which data are collected is defined *a priori* and that this level is maintained throughout all assessments.

# Box 18.3 Generating estimates of effort

*Instantaneous Counts*

To calculate the effort from an instantaneous count we denote the number of anglers counted as *C* and the time interval under consideration as T.  Then, the estimated effort is given by:

ft=CT

For example, suppose a creel clerk was to work a morning creel shift from 06:00 to 14:00 with an instantaneous count occurring at 10:15. During the count, she counted 20 anglers fishing from boats and 18 fishing from the bank. The total number of anglers, C, was 38\. The creel shift, T, was 8 hours (14:00 – 06:00).

numAnglersCounted \<- 38
shiftTime \<- 8

shiftPressure \<- numAnglersCounted \* shiftTime

The estimated angler effort for that shift is 304 angler hours.

If multiple counts are conducted, we substitute the mean count, C into the equation above.

ft=∑(Ci)mT

where C is the count for each creel count, i, and m is the total number of counts conducted.

If the creel clerk had two counts during the shift rather than the one in the previous example, and these counts were C1 \= 0 anglers (during storm) and C2 \= 65,

numAnglersCounted \<- c(0,65)
shiftTime \<- 8

shiftPressure2 \<- mean(numAnglersCounted) \* shiftTime

The estimated effort would be 260 angler hours.

*Extrapolating from shift to day*

Suppose that the creel shift the clerk was working represented half of the day.

dayPressure \<- (mean(numAnglersCounted) \* shiftTime)/0.5

The estimated effort for that day would be 520 angler hours.

*Progressive Counts*

To calculate effort from a progressive count we denote the number of anglers counted as C and the time interval to complete the circuit around the waterbody, .  Then, the estimated effort (fp) is given by:

fp=C

For example, suppose a creel clerk is working at Lake McConaughy, a 14,000-ha reservoir in western Nebraska. To travel around the reservoir (i.e., complete the circuit) takes 2 hours. During the count, he counted 21 anglers fishing from the bank and 213 anglers fishing from boats. The total number of anglers, C, is 234 anglers.

numAnglersCounted \<- c(21,213)
circuitTime \<- 2

circuitEffort \<- sum(numAnglersCounted) \* circuitTime

The estimated angler effort for that circuit is 468 468 angler hours.

Often, we would like to have an estimate for the creel shift, which is representative of a stratum (e.g., morning or afternoon period) used in the creel design. Suppose that the creel shift at Lake McConaughy is 8-hours long (T \= 14:00 – 06:00 \= 8 hours) and the 2-hour circuit was randomly chosen during that period. During this creel shift there is the potential to complete four circuits (; 8-hour workday / 2-hour circuit). The effort for the total creel shift can then be calculated as:

fp=C

numAnglersCounted \<- c(21,213)
circuitTime \<- 2
numCircuits \<- 4

circuitEffort \<- sum(numAnglersCounted) \* circuitTime \* numCircuits

The daily effort following this example would be 1872 angler hours.

*Bus Route Counts* Estimating effort is a bit more complicated than the *instantaneous* or *progressive* counts. For bus routes, we need information on the amount of time each vehicle or trailer is at each boat ramp, the total time (waiting and travel) to complete a circuit.

E=Ti=1n1wij=1meijj

where

* *E* \= estimated total party-hours of effort,

* *T* \= total time to complete a full circuit of the route, including travelling and waiting,

* *wi* \= waiting time at the *ith* site (where *i* \= 1, …, *n* sites), and

* *eij* \= total time that the *jth* car (or trailer) is parked at the *ith* site while the agent is at that site (where *j* \= 1, …, *n* sites).

As an example, suppose we have a survey at Branched Oak Lake (728 ha) in eastern Nebraska, where a creel shift starts at 12:30 and goes until 22:00 (7-hour and 45-minute shift) (Table 17.3.1). There are 7 access points with travel times to each point ranging from 15 to 30 minutes. Most of the time a clerk will spend 60 minutes at each access point, except for site 7, which is 75 minutes.

*Table 17.3.1. A bus-route schedule used to illustrate the time interval method of estimating effort and catch. The bus-route schedule covers 7 sites that begins at 12:30.*

| Site | ScheduledTime | WaitTime | TravelTime |
| ----: | :---- | ----: | ----: |
| 1 | 13:00 \- 14:00 | 60 | 30 |
| 2 | 14:30 \- 15:30 | 60 | 30 |
| 3 | 15:45 \- 16:45 | 60 | 15 |
| 4 | 17:00 \- 18:00 | 60 | 15 |
| 5 | 18:15 \- 19:15 | 60 | 15 |
| 6 | 19:30 \- 20:30 | 60 | 15 |
| 7 | 20:45 \- 22:00 | 75 | 15 |

When completing a bus route effort, each car (or trailer) that is observed at each access point is given a number. If a car is already at a site when the clerk gets there, it is assigned an arrival time of the time when the clerk reaches the site. Otherwise, the arrival time or departure time of the vehicle is recorded (Table 17.3.2). Now suppose, during the shift the clerk records five cars at site one (two cars already there, and two that were still there when the clerk departed), two cars at site two (one there at arrival and one at departure), no cars at site three and six, four cars at site four (all there still at departure), three cars at site five (all there at arrival and departure), and six cars at site seven (three at arrival and five at departure). The basic process is as follows: 1\) calculate the total time spent during a creel shift (i.e., sum the wait time and travel time), 2\) calculate the time each vehicle spent at each site (i.e., Departure time – Arrival time), 3\) sum the times for each site and divide by the probability of sampling day or night, 4\) multiply this total by the inverse of wait time at each site and take the sum across all sites, and 5\) multiple the total across all sites and multiply by the total minutes of the creel shift (step 1). The result is 16,606 party hours and, if it is assumed that there was an average of 2 anglers per party, then 33,212 angler hours.

*Mean daily estimator*

The mean-daily estimator takes creel information and digests the effort and associated variance to a single day and then extrapolates that out to the total number of the days in the month. A step by step example for both effort and catch can be found in Malvestuto et al. (1978). The approach is similar for both estimates. For the purpose of this box and to simplify the calculations, we will focus this box on estimating effort. In this example, we are going use sample data from a single month from Calamus reservoir (\~2000 ha) in central Nebraska.

*Calculate the mean angler count for boat and bank anglers per shift*

juneCount %\>%
  group\_by(date,period,section) %\>%
  summarise(meanBank \= mean(bankAnglers),
            meanBoat \= mean(boatAnglers)) \-\> dailyMeanCount

*Calculate the mean daily effort within each strata (weekdays, weekend days)*

dailyEffort %\>%
  ungroup() %\>% \# remove the previous grouping
  pivot\_longer(bankDayHours:boatDayHours, names\_to \= "anglerType", values\_to \= "dailyEffort") %\>% \# move from wide format to long format
  mutate(anglerType \= case\_when(anglerType \== "bankDayHours" \~ "Bank", \# simplify angler type
                          anglerType \== "boatDayHours" \~ "Boat"),
         date \= ymd(date), \# use lubridate to convert date to a date object
         month \= month(date, label \= TRUE), \# get the month for each date
         strata \= ifelse(wday(date,label \= TRUE) %in% c("Sat","Sun"),"weekendday","weekday")) %\>% \# identify whether each day is a weekend day or week day
  group\_by(month, anglerType, strata) %\>%
  summarise(meanDailyEffort \= mean(dailyEffort), \# calculate mean daily effort
            varDailyEffort \= var(dailyEffort), \# calculate variance of effort
            nDaysSampled \= n()) \-\> meanDailyEffort \# calculate the actual number of days sampled

*Calculate a weighted daily estimate*

\# create a data frame that describes the number of weekdays, weekend days, and total days per month
tibble(month \= "Jun",
       strata \= c("weekday","weekendday"),
       nDays \= c(8,22),
       ttlDays \= 30\) \-\> daysPerMonth

left\_join(meanDailyEffort, daysPerMonth, by \= c("month", "strata")) %\>%  \# join the days per month with the effort per strata data
  group\_by(month, anglerType) %\>%
  mutate(strataDailyEffort \= (nDays \* meanDailyEffort)/ ttlDays, \# calculate mean daily effort per strata
         strataDailyEffort \= ifelse(is.nan(strataDailyEffort), 0, strataDailyEffort), \# if variance is not-a-number (i.e., 0/0) convert to a zero
         strataWeight \= nDays/ttlDays, \# create a weight of the number of days within a strata to the total number in the month
         var1 \= (strataWeight^2 \* varDailyEffort)/nDaysSampled, \# variance calculations
         var2 \= (strataWeight \* varDailyEffort)/ttlDays) %\>%
  summarize(dailyEffortMean \= sum(strataDailyEffort), \# add the daily effort of the estimates
            dailyEffortVar \= sum(var1) \- sum(var2), \# caulate variances
            seEffort \= sqrt(dailyEffortVar), \# calculate square roots
            ttlDays \= mean(ttlDays)) \-\> overallDailyEffort \# carry forward the total days per month

overallDailyEffort

*Strata estimator*

The strata estimator is similar to the mean daily estimator but instead of creating a mean day, it retains the mean and variance of the estimates within the strata. To get monthly estimates, we extrapolate within strata and then add the estimates and variance. A good example of the strata approach for for both effort and catch can be found in Rasmussen et al. (1998).

\# Caculate daily estimates of effort the same as in the above example
juneCount %\>%
  group\_by(date,period,section) %\>%
  summarise(meanBank \= mean(bankAnglers),
            meanBoat \= mean(boatAnglers),
            nCounts \= n()) %\>%
  mutate(bankHours \= meanBank \* 8,
         boatHours \= meanBoat \* 8,
         bankDayHours \= bankHours/0.5,
         boatDayHours \= boatHours/0.5) \-\> dailyEffort

*Calculate mean strata effort estimates*

dailyEffort %\>%
  ungroup() %\>%
  select(date, bankDayHours,boatDayHours) %\>% \# select specific comments
  pivot\_longer(bankDayHours:boatDayHours, names\_to \= "anglerType", values\_to \= "dailyEffort") %\>% \# wide to long format
  mutate(anglerType \= case\_when(anglerType \== "bankDayHours" \~ "Bank", \# simplify angler type
                          anglerType \== "boatDayHours" \~ "Boat"),
         date \= ymd(date), \# convert to date format
         month \= month(date, label \= TRUE), \# add month
         strata \= ifelse(wday(date,label \= TRUE) %in% c("Sat","Sun"),"weekendday","weekday")) %\>% \# add what kind of strata
  group\_by(month, strata, anglerType) %\>%
  summarise(meanStrataEffort \= mean(dailyEffort), \#mean effort
            sb2 \= var(dailyEffort), \# among day effort variance
            nSampled \= n\_distinct(date)) %\>%  \# number of days sampled
  left\_join(daysPerMonth, by \= c("month", "strata")) %\>% \# join to the number of days per month
  mutate(strataEffort \= meanStrataEffort \* nDays) \-\> effort2 \# extrapolate effort within strata

\#\# \# Groups:   month, strata \[2\]

\#\# 2 Jun   weekd… Boat                  328   6.20e4       10     8      30

\#\# 4 Jun   weeke… Boat                  827\.  1.86e5        7    22      30

*The strata estimator and multiple counts per shift allows us to include within daily variance to estimates.* In this process, we broke the components of variance into different components as described in @.

juneCount %\>%
  pivot\_longer(bankAnglers:boatAnglers, names\_to \= "anglerType", values\_to \= "effort") %\>%
  mutate(hours \= effort \* 8,
         dayHours \= hours/0.5) %\>% \# extrapolate effort out
  group\_by(date, anglerType) %\>%
  mutate(meanEffort \= mean(dayHours), \# mean effort
         diffSq \= (dayHours \- meanEffort)^2) %\>%  \# difference from mean squared
  summarise(sumDiff \= sum(diffSq), \# sum of the squared difference
            nCounts \= n()) \-\> dailyVar1 \# number of daily counts

\# Within day variance
dailyVar1 %\>%
  ungroup() %\>%
  mutate(date \= ymd(date), \# date
         month \= month(date, label \= TRUE), \# month
         strata \= ifelse(wday(date,label \= TRUE) %in% c("Sat","Sun"),"weekendday","weekday")) %\>% \# strata
  \# left\_join(daysPerMonth, by \= c("month", "strata")) %\>%
  group\_by(month, strata, anglerType,nCounts) %\>%
  summarise(strataSum \= sum(sumDiff), \# sum of the difference
            nSampled \= n()) %\>% \# number of days sampled
  mutate(withinDayVar \= strataSum/(nSampled\*(nCounts-1))) \-\> withinDayVar \# caclulate within day variance

dailyVar1 %\>%
  ungroup() %\>%
  mutate(date \= ymd(date), \# date
         month \= month(date, label \= TRUE), \# month
         strata \= ifelse(wday(date,label \= TRUE) %in% c("Sat","Sun"),"weekendday","weekday")) %\>%  \#strata
  group\_by(month, strata, anglerType,nCounts) %\>%
  summarise(strataSum \= sum(sumDiff), \# sum of the difference
            nSampled \= n()) %\>% \# number of days sampled
  ungroup() %\>%
  mutate(sw2 \= strataSum/(nSampled\*(nCounts-1)), \# component of variance
         anglerType \= case\_when(anglerType \== "bankAnglers" \~ "Bank", \# simplify angler type
                          anglerType \== "boatAnglers" \~ "Boat")) \-\> sw2

 sw2 %\>%
   select(month, strata, anglerType, sw2) %\>%
   full\_join(effort2) %\>% \# join with effort data
   mutate(var\_y2bar \= (((1-(nSampled/nDays))/nSampled)\*sb2) \+ (1/(2\*nDays))\*sw2, \# component of variance
          strataVar \= (nDays^2) \* var\_y2bar)  %\>%  \# strata variance
   select(month, strata, anglerType, strataEffort, strataVar)  %\>%
   group\_by(month, anglerType) %\>%
   summarise(ttlEffort \= sum(strataEffort), \# monthly effort
             ttlVar \= sum(strataVar)) %\>%  \# monthly variance
   mutate(effortSE \= sqrt(ttlVar), \# standard error
          effortCIlo \= ttlEffort \- 1.96 \* effortSE, \# confidence interval
          effortCIhi \= ttlEffort \+ 1.96 \* effortSE) \-\> strataEstimators

\#\# character vector

      data.frame(type \= "MeanDaily", meanDailyEstimator)) \-\> effortEstimator

In this example, we can see that the point estimates are fairly consistent between the two methods. The large difference is the amount of variance captured around the estimates. There are a couple of reasons for this. The strata estimator included the within day variance and the mean daily did not.

When we calculate the catch rates, we must take into account whether the interview was complete or incomplete. Pollock et al. (1997) identified important issues concerning the point estimates and variances when catches were estimated from roving (mostly incomplete surveys) or from access point (complete surveys). We will walk through an example of a hybrid approach that uses complete survey information and incomplete survey information.

*Completed or access interviews*

partyCatch %\>%
  filter(tripType \== "complete") %\>%
  mutate(partyEffort \= ((timeFishedHours\*60+timeFishedMins)/60)\*numAnglers) %\>% \# effort in decimal hours
  group\_by(month, strata, anglerType, speciesCaught, catchType) %\>%
  summarise(ttlNum \= sum(numCaught), \# total number caught
            ttlAnglers \= sum(numAnglers), \# total number of anglers
            ttlTime \= sum(partyEffort), \# tota effort
            varF \= var(numCaught), \#variance of fish caught
            varH \= var(partyEffort),\# variance of party effort
            fbar2 \= mean(numCaught)^2,
            hbar2 \= mean(partyEffort)^2,
            fhbar2 \= mean(numCaught\*partyEffort)^2,
            covfh \= cov(numCaught,partyEffort), \# covariance
            k \= n\_distinct(partyID)) %\>%
  mutate(rate \= (ttlNum/ttlAnglers)/(ttlTime), \# ratio of the means
         varRate \= ((1/k)\*rate^2)\*((varF/fbar2)+((varH/hbar2))+(covfh/fhbar2)), \# variance of the catch rates
         varRate \= ifelse(is.nan(varRate),0,varRate)) %\>% \# correct for is not a number
  select(-ttlAnglers, \-ttlTime, \-ttlNum, \-varF, \-varH, \-fbar2, \-hbar2, \-fhbar2, \-covfh, k) \-\> strataComplRates

\# Mean of the ratios
